1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:05,340
Lists allow you to access elements using an index, starting from zero.

2

00:00:05,340  -->  00:00:10,720
Think of an index as the relative position of an item around other things.

3

00:00:10,720  -->  00:00:14,000
Before your favorite band performs at the Big Stadium,

4

00:00:14,000  -->  00:00:17,580
attendees file into the stadium in an orderly fashion.

5

00:00:17,580  -->  00:00:21,780
There's somebody who entered first, second, third,

6

00:00:21,780  -->  00:00:27,880
fourth, all the way to being the 1,000th or even 10,000th person.

7

00:00:27,880  -->  00:00:30,780
The order is incredibly important for lists,

8

00:00:30,780  -->  00:00:32,435
which you will see in a bit.

9

00:00:32,435  -->  00:00:36,430
Something that can be quite confusing that you should remember is

10

00:00:36,430  -->  00:00:40,565
that the first index of a position is actually zero.

11

00:00:40,565  -->  00:00:44,510
While the order might be person 1, 2,

12

00:00:44,510  -->  00:00:46,230
3, and so on,

13

00:00:46,230  -->  00:00:48,530
person one's index is zero.

14

00:00:48,530  -->  00:00:50,770
Person 2 's index is one,

15

00:00:50,770  -->  00:00:53,930
person 3 's index is two, and so on.

16

00:00:53,930  -->  00:00:58,550
Make sure to keep that in mind as you go about using indexes.

17

00:00:58,550  -->  00:01:00,670
Once we have a list of items,

18

00:01:00,670  -->  00:01:03,610
we might want to select only a subsection of

19

00:01:03,610  -->  00:01:07,595
that list or pull certain items out of that big list.

20

00:01:07,595  -->  00:01:11,740
Think of this like a crane going into a basket of prizes.

21

00:01:11,740  -->  00:01:13,760
When you are slicing a list,

22

00:01:13,760  -->  00:01:19,220
you can pull out a single item or a collection of items that are next to each other.

23

00:01:19,220  -->  00:01:23,700
Slicing uses the format, start, colon, end,

24

00:01:23,700  -->  00:01:26,380
where start is the index to begin at,

25

00:01:26,380  -->  00:01:28,660
and end is the index up to,

26

00:01:28,660  -->  00:01:30,980
but not including that number.

27

00:01:30,980  -->  00:01:34,960
Let's see an example of lists in action with

28

00:01:34,960  -->  00:01:40,105
our fruit list example from before using indexing, and then slicing.

29

00:01:40,105  -->  00:01:45,090
Lists allow you to access elements using an index starting with zero.

30

00:01:45,090  -->  00:01:48,550
We'll define a list with a variable name,

31

00:01:48,550  -->  00:01:50,550
which we'll call fruits, and then we'll use

32

00:01:50,550  -->  00:01:53,290
square brackets and then put items inside of it.

33

00:01:53,290  -->  00:01:55,990
Here we have three strings, apple,

34

00:01:55,990  -->  00:01:59,490
banana, and cherry, indicating our three fruits.

35

00:01:59,490  -->  00:02:05,810
If we want to print the first item, how do you think we would do that?

36

00:02:06,290  -->  00:02:11,770
What do you think the first index would be as an index zero?

37

00:02:12,530  -->  00:02:16,130
To write this, we'd write fruits.

38

00:02:16,130  -->  00:02:18,550
We'll use a square bracket.

39

00:02:18,550  -->  00:02:21,410
We'll put zero for the first item,

40

00:02:21,410  -->  00:02:24,435
and the square bracket, and then we'll close out our print statement.

41

00:02:24,435  -->  00:02:28,070
What do you think the index of zero will be?

42

00:02:29,120  -->  00:02:31,610
If you guess apple, you're right.

43

00:02:31,610  -->  00:02:33,530
It's the first item in the array,

44

00:02:33,530  -->  00:02:36,050
and thus index position zero.

45

00:02:36,050  -->  00:02:41,590
You can also retrieve a slice of a list using the slicing syntax.

46

00:02:41,590  -->  00:02:45,510
Again, we'll take our list from before,

47

00:02:45,510  -->  00:02:48,210
and we'll paste that into a new cell.

48

00:02:48,750  -->  00:02:54,350
If we want to slice out part of our list,

49

00:02:54,350  -->  00:02:58,570
such as the first index to the third index,

50

00:02:58,570  -->  00:03:01,550
what do you think the output of this will be?

51

00:03:01,550  -->  00:03:05,690
If we do fruits, do a square bracket.

52

00:03:05,690  -->  00:03:08,645
We'll do one colon 3,

53

00:03:08,645  -->  00:03:11,050
and then we'll close out that statement.

54

00:03:11,050  -->  00:03:13,430
What do you think the output will be here?

55

00:03:13,430  -->  00:03:16,350
Let's run it and find out.

56

00:03:16,630  -->  00:03:24,545
This is going to retrieve the elements from index one up to but not including index 3.

57

00:03:24,545  -->  00:03:29,030
It will skip apple at index zero, our first element,

58

00:03:29,030  -->  00:03:31,710
and then we'll print the first index,

59

00:03:31,710  -->  00:03:35,310
which is banana up to the third index,

60

00:03:35,310  -->  00:03:40,810
which is cherry, because it will include that,

61

00:03:40,810  -->  00:03:46,170
and then once it reaches the third index element, then it would stop.

62

00:03:46,170  -->  00:03:48,215
But we only have 0,

63

00:03:48,215  -->  00:03:51,030
1, 2 index items.

64

00:03:51,030  -->  00:03:53,190
But since we said third,

65

00:03:53,190  -->  00:03:55,990
that's why it includes cherry.
